title: Storage
content:
3. Verify Storage Driver Settings:

Incompatibilities with storage drivers can cause Docker to fail during startup. Check your storage driver settings in Docker's configuration file:​

bash
Copy
cat /etc/docker/daemon.json

If the file doesn't exist or is empty, consider creating or modifying it to specify a compatible storage



sudo systemctl restart docker

5. Ensure Kernel Compatibility:


Verify that your Proxmox LXC container's kernel supports Docker's requirements. Docker requires specific kernel features, and using an unsupported kernel can lead to startup failures. Consider updating your kernel or adjusting your container's configuration to ensure compatibility.​


6. Review System Resources:


Insufficient system resources, such as memory or CPU, can cause Docker to fail to start. Check your system's resource usage:​


bash

Copy

free -h

top

If resources are constrained, consider allocating more resources to your LXC container or optimizing existing workloads.​


7. Reinstall Docker:


If the issue persists, consider reinstalling Docker to ensure all components are correctly installed:​


bash

Copy

sudo apt-get remove --purge docker.io

sudo apt-get install docker.io

After reinstallation, start the Docker service:​

cat /etc/docker/daemon.json

If the file doesn't exist or is empty, consider creating or modifying it to specify a compatible storage driver, such as overlay2:​

CSDN Blog


json

Copy

{

 "storage-driver": "overlay2"

}

After making changes, restart Docker:

bash

Copy

sudo systemctl start docker

8. Consult Docker Documentation and Community Forums:


If you've tried all the above steps without success, refer to the official Docker documentation for further guidance. Additionally, engaging with the Docker Community Forums can provide insights from other users who may have encountered similar issues.​


By systematically following these steps, you should be able to identify and resolve the issue preventing Docker from starting on your Proxmox LXC container.
